reviews.review_text: The wonders of bathroom connections Ran into a plumber in the bathroom at the Buffalo Memorial Auditorium and he helped me plumb some of this and that, which certainly helped in seeing third eye to third eye with this great show. The excellent first set with that lacivious Lazy Lightnin/Supplication and Jack Straw powerhouse prepared the table nicely for that second set exploration of extravagance. Those wonder-us Dancin' in the Streets surely got the faithful in a frenzy to be followed by that majestic Tower of Franklin. The Caution jam out of He's Gone was a great mindbender. All in all, big fun with a big band at the height of their powers.
Standard set list, and standard playing until after Drums/Space, at which point they pull out all the stops. Recording good, but crowd-heavy.

Damned Good Show For '79 Well njpg, you're a tough man to please.  I went over this show with a fine-tooth comb and I'll be damned if I can find any reason for not giving this baby the highest rating.  It's got everything you'd want in wishing you were there, "average" set list or not, whatever that means?

Jerry sounds good (which is not the norm in '79 (with the week before being absolutely horrid)); the first set closes with a very nice Jack Straw; the second opens with a spirited Dancing with a beautiful and very well done seque into an excellent Franklin's; we get a Caution from He's Gone; the end of the second is flat-out with a nice encore; and the recording is damn good with fabulous fidelity.  And yes, it's crowd heavy with quite a bit of hand-held crowd clapping with some crazy chick a couple of seats away being more funny than annoying.  But hey, with it being exceptionally difficult to find really high quality shows that include Jerry singing well in '79, how could you not give this anything but the highest rating.  I don't know about you but, there seems like some much-appreciated "X" Factor energy circulating around tonight.  I'm certainly comfortable declaring it being in da house.  As far as I'm concerned, I recommend this show highly - as long as you're a serious maven of the crowd.  If not, stay far, far away from this upload.
bread crumb Promised Land was played 434 times, more or less.  After its introduction in mid-1971, coincident to nothing I can discern, it is played without haitus.  Must be easy to remember.

A great show! Two things stood out on this gread AUD pull: the segue from Dancin' into Franklin's is one of the smoothest and most seamless segues I have ever heard (and the short but ripping end to Franklin's is pretty nice, too!) And the Wharf Rat in general - and the way Jerry draws out the "everyone saaaaaiiid" line in particular (right around the 2:30 mark) reminded me immediately of another great Wharf Rat - from Irvine CA., 4-19-87.  This is a GREAT show, and well worth the listen!!
